$36 million domestic this past weekend=E2=80=94more than Captain Underpants=
, also adapted from a Pilkey kid-lit series, which opened to $24 million in=
 2017. Aside from being an unusually lucrative debut for an animated film i=
n January, it is also the latest evidence that Universal=E2=80=99s non-Illu=
mination animation label can mint new franchises from popular, but not ubiq=
uitous, material. This follows recent
successes like The Bad Guys ($250 million in 2022) and The Wild Robot, whic=
h earned $325 million last year and has a slew of award nominations. Both o=
f the latter were also adapted from popular children=E2=80=99s books.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

A burning question: Why aren=E2=80=99t more animated kids movies trying to =
capitalize on the market opportunity? After Dog Man, the next cartoon from =
a major studio=E2=80=94Pixar=E2=80=99s
Elio=E2=80=94won=E2=80=99t arrive until June. Alas, this isn=E2=80=99t exac=
tly a new problem. In the earlier days of the Covid theatrical recovery, su=
ch as it was, theaters went months between DreamWorks=E2=80=99 Puss in Boot=
s: The Last Wish, in December 2022, and Illumination=E2=80=99s The Super Ma=
rio Bros. Movie in April 2023, both of which were Universal releases. But t=
hat drought was more understandable given the holiday season.=C2=A0

