=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Dog Man</em>, DreamWorks Animation=E2=
=80=99s $40 million adaptation
of <strong>Dav Pilkey</strong>=E2=80=99s mega-popular graphic novel series,=
 nabbed a robust $36 million domestic this past weekend=E2=80=94more than <=
em>Captain Underpants</em>, also adapted from a Pilkey kid-lit series, whic=
h opened to $24 million in 2017. Aside from being an unusually lucrative de=
but for an animated film in January, it is also the latest evidence that Un=
iversal=E2=80=99s <em>non</em>-Illumination animation label can mint new fr=
anchises from popular, but not ubiquitous, material. This follows recent
successes like <em>The Bad Guys</em> ($250 million in 2022) and <em>The Wil=
d Robot</em>, which earned $325 million last year and has a slew of award n=
ominations. Both of the latter were also adapted from popular children=E2=
=80=99s books.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p>=
<p style=3D"margin:0;">A burning question: Why aren=E2=80=99t more animated=
 kids movies trying to capitalize on the market opportunity? After <em>Dog =
Man</em>, the next cartoon from a major studio=E2=80=94Pixar=E2=80=99s
<em>Elio</em>=E2=80=94won=E2=80=99t arrive until June. Alas, this isn=E2=80=
=99t exactly a new problem. In the earlier days of the Covid theatrical rec=
overy, such as it was, theaters went <em>months</em> between DreamWorks=E2=
=80=99 <em>Puss in Boots: The Last Wish</em>, in December 2022, and Illumin=
ation=E2=80=99s <em>The Super Mario Bros. Movie </em>in April 2023, both of=
 which were Universal releases. But that drought was more understandable gi=
ven the holiday season.=C2=A0</p></div>
